Biology. Specimens found in medium to fine sand bottoms in the zone of initial dilution of the Barbers Point outfall and at reference stations of the Sand Island, Barbers Point and Waianae outfalls. This species has been commonly found in low abundance in these regions with organic enrichment since the beginning of the monitoring in 1986 and they seem to be resilient to the sewage plume. This sphaerodorid was also collected from almost 500 m depth off the south shore of Oahu during a study of harbor dredge disposal sites. These deeper localities have received dredge spoil sediments from Honolulu and Pearl Harbors over the last few decades and deposits of more than 30 cm thickness cover relict natural sediments and reefs (
Hampton et al. 1997
).
